01:01:03.600 --> 01:01:08.560
So let's wrap this up with just getting your perspective and your thoughts.

01:01:08.660 --> 01:01:10.540
You talked about LLMs a little bit.

01:01:11.640 --> 01:01:15.640
We saw that spaCy can integrate with LLMs, which is pretty interesting,

01:01:15.700 --> 01:01:17.720
and you definitely do a whole chapter of that on the course.

01:01:20.380 --> 01:01:26.420
Is spaCy still relevant in the age of LLMs and such and such?

01:01:26.880 --> 01:01:28.380
Yeah, people keep asking me that question.

01:01:29.480 --> 01:01:32.000
So the way I would approach all this LLM stuff

01:01:32.380 --> 01:01:34.580
is approach it with curiosity.

01:01:35.080 --> 01:01:37.040
I will definitely agree that there's

01:01:37.680 --> 01:01:39.500
interesting stuff happening there, for sure.

01:01:41.680 --> 01:01:44.340
Oh, a little connection hiccup, but I think we're back.

01:01:44.860 --> 01:01:48.080
So the way I would really try to look at these LLMs

01:01:48.100 --> 01:01:49.520
is to sort of say, well, I'm curious,

01:01:49.680 --> 01:01:51.300
and therefore I'm going to go ahead and explore it.

01:01:51.760 --> 01:01:53.840
But it is also a fundamentally new field

01:01:54.060 --> 01:01:56.840
where there's downsides like prompt injection

01:01:56.960 --> 01:02:01.640
And there's downsides like compute costs and just money costs and all of those sorts of things.

01:02:02.939 --> 01:02:06.260
And it's not like the old tool suddenly doesn't work anymore.

01:02:06.950 --> 01:02:10.820
But the cool thing about spaCy is you can easily run it on your own data sets and on your own hardware.

01:02:11.050 --> 01:02:13.800
And it's easier to inspect and all of those sorts of things.

01:02:14.880 --> 01:02:18.880
So by all means, definitely check out the LLMs because there's cool things you can do with it.

01:02:19.810 --> 01:02:20.900
But I don't think that spaCy...

01:02:20.920 --> 01:02:23.880
Like the idea of having a specific model locally,

01:02:24.460 --> 01:02:27.340
I don't think that that's going to go anywhere anytime soon.

01:02:27.520 --> 01:02:29.940
And you can read a couple of the Explosion blog posts.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:31.640
Back when I was there, we actually did some benchmarks.

01:02:32.360 --> 01:02:35.440
So like if you just do everything with like a prompt in ChatGPT,

01:02:35.600 --> 01:02:38.000
say here's the text, here's the thing I want you to detect in it,

01:02:38.420 --> 01:02:39.120
please detect it.

01:02:39.200 --> 01:02:41.540
Like how good is that compared to training your own custom model?

01:02:43.320 --> 01:02:46.180
I think once you have about like a thousand labels

01:02:46.360 --> 01:02:47.920
or 5,000 somewhere in that ballpark,

01:02:48.600 --> 01:02:50.660
the smaller, spaCy-ish model

01:02:50.900 --> 01:02:52.120
seems to be performing better already.

01:02:53.900 --> 01:02:55.760
And sure, who knows what the future holds,

01:02:55.770 --> 01:02:56.900
but I do think that that will

01:02:58.060 --> 01:02:59.840
probably not change anytime soon.

01:03:01.600 --> 01:03:02.620
Yeah, you got to be careful what you say

01:03:02.780 --> 01:03:03.180
about the future,

01:03:03.440 --> 01:03:04.200
because this is getting written

01:03:04.320 --> 01:03:05.000
into the transcript

01:03:05.580 --> 01:03:06.220
and stored there

01:03:06.580 --> 01:03:07.760
in the Arctic vault and everything.

01:03:08.500 --> 01:03:08.960
No, I'm just kidding.

01:03:10.120 --> 01:03:11.360
Yeah, well, I mean...

01:03:12.180 --> 01:03:13.140
No, I agree with you.

01:03:14.359 --> 01:03:16.120
The main thing I do believe in

01:03:16.130 --> 01:03:17.200
is I do want to be a voice

01:03:17.340 --> 01:03:18.380
that kind of goes against the hype.

01:03:18.480 --> 01:03:36.800
I do have LLMs more and more now, and I do see the merit of them, and I do think people should explore it with curiosity, but I am not in favor of LLM maximalism. That's a phrase that a colleague of mine from Explosion used to coin, but LLM maximalism is probably not going to be that productive.

01:03:39.440 --> 01:03:49.600
Yeah, I've tried to, for example, I've tried to take the transcripts from Talk Python and put them into ChatGPT just to have a conversation about them, ask it a question or something.

01:03:50.160 --> 01:03:53.640
You know, like, for example, hey, give me the top five takeaways from this.

01:03:53.650 --> 01:03:58.200
And maybe I could put that as like a little header of the show to help people decide if they want to listen.

01:03:59.860 --> 01:04:01.880
It can't even parse one transcript.

01:04:02.620 --> 01:04:03.500
It's probably too long.

01:04:04.060 --> 01:04:04.440
It's too long.

01:04:04.600 --> 01:04:04.760
Exactly.

01:04:04.950 --> 01:04:06.840
It goes over the context window.

01:04:07.160 --> 01:04:13.640
And so, for example, the project that you did in the course, it chowed through nine years of it, right?

01:04:13.740 --> 01:04:15.080
I mean, it doesn't answer the same questions.

01:04:15.760 --> 01:04:20.560
But if you're not asking those open-ended questions, you know, then it's pretty awesome.

01:04:21.680 --> 01:04:22.540
I guess there's like maybe two.

01:04:22.670 --> 01:04:24.960
Like one, definitely have a look at Claude as well.

01:04:25.010 --> 01:04:27.000
Like I have been impressed with their context length.

01:04:27.980 --> 01:04:29.020
It could still fail.

01:04:29.070 --> 01:04:32.760
But like there are also other LLMs that have more specialized needs, I suppose.

01:04:33.800 --> 01:04:37.260
I guess one thing, keeping NLP in the back of your mind,

01:04:37.610 --> 01:04:39.320
one thing or use case, I guess,

01:04:39.350 --> 01:04:40.680
that I would want to maybe mention

01:04:40.900 --> 01:04:42.580
that is really awesome with LLMs,

01:04:42.630 --> 01:04:43.780
and I've been doing this a ton recently,

01:04:46.040 --> 01:04:47.140
a trick that I always like to use

01:04:47.140 --> 01:04:50.400
in terms of what examples should I annotate first?

01:04:51.340 --> 01:04:52.340
At some point, you've got to imagine

01:04:52.350 --> 01:04:53.720
I have some sort of spaCy model.

01:04:54.400 --> 01:04:56.140
Maybe it has like 200 data points of labels.

01:04:56.280 --> 01:04:57.820
It's not the best model, but it's an okay model.

01:04:58.660 --> 01:05:01.180
And then I might compare that to what I get out of an LLM.

01:05:02.960 --> 01:05:04.220
When those two models disagree,

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:06.720
something interesting is usually happening.

01:05:07.660 --> 01:05:09.080
Because the LLM model is pretty good

01:05:09.190 --> 01:05:10.340
and the spaCy model is pretty good.

01:05:10.370 --> 01:05:11.080
But when they disagree,

01:05:11.940 --> 01:05:13.240
then I'm probably dealing with

01:05:13.690 --> 01:05:15.120
either a model that can be improved

01:05:15.360 --> 01:05:17.420
or a data point that's just kind of tricky

01:05:17.470 --> 01:05:18.240
or something like that.

01:05:19.180 --> 01:05:20.820
And using this technique of disagreement

01:05:21.060 --> 01:05:22.920
to prioritize which examples

01:05:23.050 --> 01:05:24.300
to annotate first manually,

01:05:25.200 --> 01:05:26.620
that's been proven to be super useful.

01:05:26.670 --> 01:05:27.780
And that's also the awesome thing

01:05:27.900 --> 01:05:29.400
that these LLMs give you.

01:05:29.880 --> 01:05:31.380
They will always be able to give you

01:05:31.360 --> 01:05:33.220
a second model within five minutes

01:05:33.480 --> 01:05:34.360
because all you need is a prompt.

01:05:34.910 --> 01:05:36.280
And it doesn't matter if it's not perfect

01:05:36.510 --> 01:05:37.700
because I only need it for annotation.

01:05:38.540 --> 01:05:39.660
And that use case has proven,

01:05:39.830 --> 01:05:41.160
like I do believe that that use case

01:05:41.230 --> 01:05:43.280
has been proven demonstrably at this point.

01:05:43.390 --> 01:05:44.620
So that's what people should use.

01:05:45.040 --> 01:05:45.960
That's the trick that people should use.

01:05:48.200 --> 01:05:48.440
Amazing.

01:05:49.240 --> 01:05:51.480
Yeah, so I learned a bunch from all this stuff.

01:05:51.530 --> 01:05:53.780
I think it's super cool.

01:05:54.140 --> 01:05:57.440
There's lots of use cases that I can think of

01:05:57.720 --> 01:05:59.180
that would be really fun.

01:05:59.310 --> 01:06:01.080
Like if you're running a customer service thing,

01:06:01.200 --> 01:06:02.520
You could do sentiment analysis.

01:06:03.600 --> 01:06:07.720
If the person seems angry, you're like, if you're CrowdStrike, you know, just for example.

